Sending side:


ipc_send_message()
  - if return other than IPC_OK, user needs to free the buffer.
  - Calls *dest_port_info->port_send_vector(out_msg, dest_port_info);
  - port_send_vector points to either ipc_send_reliable_message(),
    ipc_send_unreliable message() or ipc_send_unrel_not_message().

ipc_send_message_blocked()
  - if return other than IPC_OK or IPC_TIMEOUT, user needs to free the buffer.
  - call ipc_send_message() to deliver the message.
  - will NOT free message buffer if initial sanity checks are passed.


ipc_send_unreliable_message()
  - ipc_output()
  - ipc_return_message()

ipc_send_reliable_message()
  - check flow control
  - msg_id_hi seems to be incremented for every message sent
  - msg_id_lo points to the payload address
  - after a timeout, will sync the sequence number. This is done by
    flagging the first message after a timeout with IPC_FLAG_SEQ_SYNC.
    (Client detect timeout, and flag the first message after timeout)
  - call ipc_assign_sequence_and_send()

  - queue message on ipc_message_table if it is ready to send.
    Otherwise queue it in dest_port_info->msgQ.

  - Seems ipc_message_table is for ACK lookup.



Receiving side:

ACK is processed by ipc_process_ack_message().
NACK is processed by ipc_process_nack_message().

ipc_process_ack_message()
  - will always ack with the last heard sequence
  - if a future ACK is received, all older message will be freed or notified.


---------------------------------------------------------

If the sequence number jump ahead, SUP will not response (no ACK or NACK).
But when the sequence number is correct, SUP will resume to ACK.

If the sequence number jumps backward, SUP will response with
repeated ACK for the last message with correct sequence number
(in sequence number and msg_id).


